aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident Analysis - FK LIGHTPLANES FK9 ELA SW in Canton, Georgia
The accident occurred in Canton, Georgia.
The accident occurred on January 4, 2014.
The accident occurred at 15:30 Local time.
The aircraft involved was an FK LIGHTPLANES FK9 ELA SW.
The defining event of the accident was landing gear collapse.
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was ERA14LA089.
The aircraft registration was N611SP.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There were 2 occupants in the aircraft.
No injuries were sustained by any occupants.
The pilot reported the engine experienced a partial power loss during cruise flight.
The airplane was unable to maintain altitude.
The pilot chose to perform an off-airport landing to an open field.
During the landing roll, the airplane encountered a berm.
The airplane became airborne after encountering the berm.
The airplane landed hard after becoming airborne.
Examination of the engine revealed the carburetor float chamber vent lines had been incorrectly routed to the air filter.
The engine manufacturer's installation manual cautioned that the float chamber vent lines must not be routed into the slipstream or down the firewall.
The engine manufacturer warned that pressure differences between the intake pressure in the carburetor chambers may lead to engine malfunction due to incorrect fuel supply.
The incorrectly installed vent line likely resulted in back pressure to the float bowl that exceeded the normal operating range.
The excessive back pressure affected the engine's fuel-air mixture.
The affected fuel-air mixture led to the partial loss of engine power.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of the accident to be a partial loss of engine power during cruise flight.
The partial loss of engine power was due to an overly lean fuel-air mixture.
The overly lean fuel-air mixture resulted from an incorrectly installed float chamber vent line.
The partial loss of engine power led to a subsequent off-airport landing.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Canton, Georgia

## Date & Time: 
January 4, 2014, 15:30 Local

## Aircraft:
FK LIGHTPLANES FK9 ELA SW

## Defining Event:
Landing gear collapse

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
ERA14LA089

## Registration:
N611SP

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
2 None

## Analysis

The pilot reported that, while in cruise flight, the engine experienced a partial power loss. The airplane was unable to maintain altitude, so the pilot chose to perform an off-airport landing to an open field. During the landing roll, the airplane encountered a berm, became airborne, and then landed hard.

Examination of the engine revealed that the carburetor float chamber vent lines had been incorrectly routed to the air filter. The engine manufacturer's installation manual cautioned that the float chamber vent lines must not be routed into the slipstream or down the firewall because "pressure differences between the intake pressure in the carburetor chambers may lead to engine malfunction due to incorrect fuel supply." Therefore, it is likely that the incorrectly installed vent line resulted in back pressure to the float bowl that exceeded the normal operating range, which would have affected the engine's fuel-air mixture and led to the partial loss of engine power.

## Probable Cause and Findings

The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:

A partial loss of engine power during cruise flight due to an overly lean fuel-air mixture, which resulted from an incorrectly installed float chamber vent line and led to a subsequent off-airport landing.
